entry.title: Red Flag Warning issued October 17 at 1:34AM CDT until October 17 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Bismarck ND
entry.summary:
...RED FLAG WARNING FOR LOGAN, LAMOURE, MCINTOSH, AND DICKEY COUNTIES THIS MORNING THROUGH THE EARLY EVENING...
.Some areas in the southern James River Valley could see a continuation of at least near- critical fire weather conditions early this morning as southerly winds persist around 20 mph and early morning humidity rises no higher than 40 percent.
Critical fire weather conditions are then expected to return to Logan, LaMoure, McIntosh, and Dickey counties Thursday morning in advance of a cold front. Southerly winds up to 30 mph and gusts to 40 mph will be possible here with afternoon humidity dipping as low as 20 percent. The cold front will lead to a wind shift in the mid to late afternoon hours, shifting the winds to out of the west and eventually the northwest.
* WINDS...South 20 to 30 mph with gusts up to 40 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...As low as 21 percent.
* AFFECTED AREA...Logan, McIntosh, LaMoure, and Dickey counties.
* IMPACTS...Any fires that ignite will spread rapidly and become difficult to control or suppress.
entry.cap:areaDesc: Logan; La Moure; McIntosh; Dickey

entry.title: Red Flag Warning issued October 16 at 9:31PM PDT until October 19 at 5:00PM PDT by NWS San Francisco CA
entry.summary:
...RED FLAG WARNING NOW IN EFFECT THURSDAY NIGHT THROUGH SATURDAY EVENING FOR THE BAY AREA AND CENTRAL COAST AS STRONG OFFSHORE WINDS AND CRITICALLY DRY CONDITIONS ARE EXPECTED TO DEVELOP...
.Gusty north-northeast winds are expected to develop as an "inside slider" system moves into the Great Basin this weekend. Humidities will still be on the higher end at the start of the event on Thursday, but are expected to quickly dry out as low as 10% Friday and Saturday. Peak winds are expected overnight Thursday night into Friday morning for the North Bay and Bay Area. Most areas across the region will be affected to some degree, with likely exceptions being the immediate Big Sur coast and the Marin/Sonoma coast. Winds largely on the order of 25- 35 mph can be expected with gusts to 50 mph...isolated gusts to 65 mph across the highest terrain and ridgetops, most notably the North Bay Interior Mountains and the Diablo Range.
* AFFECTED AREA...Fire Weather Zone 006 San Francisco, Fire Weather Zone 502 Marin Coastal Range, Fire Weather Zone 503 Sonoma Coastal Range, Fire Weather Zone 504 North Bay Interior Mountains, Fire Weather Zone 506 North Bay Interior Valleys, Fire Weather Zone 508 San Francisco Bay Shoreline, Fire Weather Zone 509 San Francisco Peninsula Coast, Fire Weather Zone 510 East Bay Interior Valleys, Fire Weather Zone 512 Santa Cruz Mountains, Fire Weather Zone 513 Santa Clara Valley Including San Jose, Fire Weather Zone 514 Eastern Santa Clara Hills, Fire Weather Zone 515 East Bay Hills and Fire Weather Zone 529 Northern Monterey Bay.
* TIMING...11 PM Thursday until 5 PM Saturday
* WINDS...North 25 to 35 mph with gusts up to 50 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...As low as 9 percent.
* LIGHTNING...None.
* IMPACTS...The combination of gusty winds and low humidity can cause fire to rapidly grow in size and intensity. Outdoor burning is not recommended. Despite recent cool weather and high humidity, we are expecting a widespread and prolonged offshore wind event which will likely dry fuels out very quickly given their volatility over the past several weeks.
entry.cap:areaDesc: San Francisco; Marin Coastal Range; Sonoma Coastal Range; North Bay Interior Mountains; North Bay Interior Valleys; San Francisco Bay Shoreline; San Fransisco Peninsula Coast; East Bay Interior Valleys; Santa Cruz Mountains; Santa Clara Valley Including San Jose; Eastern Santa Clara Hills; East Bay Hills; Northern Monterey Bay

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 16 at 3:16PM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
An arctic front will continue to move across the Interior today, bringing blustery westerly winds and accumulating snow showers with wind gusts into the 25 to 35 mph range. High pressure will then settle over the region Friday morning through Sunday morning, which will result in morning low temperatures falling across the Interior to well below seasonal normals. This will represent the coldest temps of the season thus far, with lower elevation valley locations dropping into the single digits by Friday morning. Some of the coldest valley locations will likely drop below zero Saturday morning. Residents are advised to make proper cold weather preparations in advance.
Attention then turns to a developing winter storm which is currently projected to impact the Interior late Sunday night/early Monday morning and last into the middle of next week. Significant accumulations of snowfall (greater than 6 inches) are likely across a wide swath of the Interior. Mixed rain/snow is also possible during this storm event, especially in the Tanana Valley and near the Alaska Range, so disruptions to travel are likely early next week. There is moderate confidence in gusty winds causing blowing and drifting snow along with reduced visibility as well. Additional rounds of lighter snow are likely Wednesday and Thursday.
The Interior should prepare for a much colder weekend, a snowy week next week, and should stay tuned for updates to the forecast.

entry.title: Fire Weather Watch issued October 16 at 2:45PM PDT until October 19 at 8:00PM PDT by NWS Los Angeles/Oxnard CA
entry.summary:
...FIRE WEATHER WATCH ISSUED FOR SECTIONS OF VENTURA AND LOS ANGELES COUNTIES DUE TO GUSTY OFFSHORE WINDS AND LOW RELATIVE HUMIDITY...
.Weak to moderate Santa Ana winds are expected to develop across Ventura and Los Angeles counties Friday morning with the winds continuing through Saturday evening. Northeasterly winds gusts of 25 to 40 mph will be likely across parts of Ventura and Los Angeles counties with local gusts around 50 MPH. Along with the wind, relative humidity will drop into the teens, and even locally into the single digits. This combination of gusty offshore winds and low relative humidity will bring the potential of widespread critical fire weather conditions.
The National Weather Service in Los Angeles/Oxnard has issued a Fire Weather Watch for wind and low relative humidity, which is in effect from Friday morning through Saturday evening.
* WINDS...Northeast 20 to 35 mph with gusts up to 50 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...10 TO 20 percent, but locally 5-10 percent.
* IMPACTS...If fire ignition occurs, conditions are favorable for rapid fire spread and extreme fire behavior which would threaten life and property.
